   "id": "6abec62a-a942-4e7d-96c5-8a1e04cd8e36",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Dynamic Modeling Plants-Hare-Lynx  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a40fa40a-ca61-4d0b-8aed-98bc11dce011",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Scenario 3: Chaos "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8071f360-6732-403e-9468-d8cab21f418a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Population dynamics in ecological systems can show not only stable equilibria or regular oscillations but also chaotic behavior. To differentiate chaotic behavior from the other two, it must be proven that it is deterministic, bounded, non-periodic, and sensitive to initial conditions.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this scenario, the goal was to find parameters for the plant–hare–lynx model that show chaotic behavior and also have the lynx population exhibiting two peaks in a timespan of 200 months. The second part of the assignment is to verify that these parameters indeed generate chaotic behavior by demonstrating that the properties of chaos are met.\n",
    "\n",
    "One important property is that populations remain bounded. This is caused by the structure of our equations. For example, the plant growth equation includes the term 1 - y[0], which shows that plants cannot grow indefinitely because space and resources are limited. Similarly, if lynx overconsume hares, the hare population decreases, which in turn causes the lynx population to decline due to lack of food. These feedback mechanisms naturally keep all populations within realistic limits, which is why the plots of plants, hares, and lynx appear bounded between upper and lower limits."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 32,
   "id": "c2290eea-bdbe-4951-856e-0b85bddb61e6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1000x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 800x600 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from scipy.integrate import solve_ivp\n",
    "from scipy.optimize import least_squares\n",
    "\n",
    "# Define the 3-species system of ODEs\n",
    "def plants_hare_lynx(t, y, a1, a2, b1, b2, d1, d2):\n",
    "    dy0 = y[0]*(1-y[0]) - ((a1*y[0])/(1+b1*y[0]))*y[1]\n",
    "    dy1 = ((a1*y[0])/(1+b1*y[0]))*y[1] - d1*y[1] - (a2*y[1]/(1+b2*y[1]))*y[2]\n",
    "    dy2 = (a2*y[1]/(1+b2*y[1]))*y[2] - d2*y[2]\n",
    "    return [dy0, dy1, dy2]\n",
    "\n",
    "t0 = 0                    # start time of simulation [in months]\n",
    "tfinal = 200              # end time of simulation [in months]\n",
    "y0 = [0.8, 0.2, 8.0]      # initial state: [plants, hares, lynx] at t=0\n",
    "tspan = (t0, tfinal)      # time span\n",
    "\n",
    "# Senario 3: Parameters \n",
    "a1, a2 = 5.001, 0.1001    # the rate of eating plants and hunting hares \n",
    "b1, b2 = 3.0, 2.0         # the maximum consumption possible for both plants and hares \n",
    "d1, d2 = 0.41, 0.011      # the death rate of both hares and lynx \n",
    "\n",
    "# The system of ODEs is solved numerically\n",
    "t_eval = np.linspace(t0, tfinal, 1000)\n",
    "sol = solve_ivp(lambda t, y: plants_hare_lynx(t, y, a1, a2, b1, b2, d1, d2),\n",
    "                tspan, y0, t_eval=t_eval, method='RK23')\n",
    "\n",
    "# To plot population over time\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))\n",
    "ax.plot(sol.t, sol.y[0], label='Plants', color='green')\n",
    "ax.plot(sol.t, sol.y[1], label='Hares', color='blue')\n",
    "ax.plot(sol.t, sol.y[2], label='Lynx', color='red')\n",
    "ax.set_title('Plant-Hare-Lynx Populations Over Time')\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Time [months]')\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Population')\n",
    "ax.legend(loc='upper right')\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "# To plot 3D state space\n",
    "fig2 = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))\n",
    "ax2 = fig2.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')\n",
    "ax2.plot(sol.y[0], sol.y[1], sol.y[2], color='black')\n",
    "ax2.set_title('State space')\n",
    "ax2.set_xlabel('Plants')\n",
    "ax2.set_ylabel('Hares')\n",
    "ax2.set_zlabel('Lynx')\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d97f8ee9-7f2f-42b3-aad3-af1abb8ec25d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Non-Periodic Dynamics"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "dc0c6496-1b45-4fd6-9d83-a113e60f6844",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can see from the following plots of population over time that the population never reaches stable repeating oscillations. Each peak is **different** from the previous one. If the system had been periodic, this fluctuation would not happen and we would easily be able to predict the next peak. \n",
    "\n",
    "In the state-space, we see that each period shows a different pattern than the previous one (even after 2000 months). This is also an indicator that the system is not periodic. If it had been periodic the system would (eventually) stabilize and 'draw' the same pattern over and over again ; we would not be seeing these ellipses of different sizes.   "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "id": "85468361-5e6f-4cee-89dc-f4338577fba6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1400x500 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "sol_s3_long = solve_ivp(plants_hare_lynx, (0, 2000), y0,\n",
    "                        args=(a1, a2, b1, b2, d1, d2),\n",
    "                        t_eval=np.linspace(0, 2000, 20000), max_step=0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(14, 5))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Time series\n",
    "axes[0].plot(sol_s3_long.t, sol_s3_long.y[0], label='Plants', color='green', lw=0.5)\n",
    "axes[0].plot(sol_s3_long.t, sol_s3_long.y[1], label='Hares', color='orange', lw=0.5)\n",
    "axes[0].plot(sol_s3_long.t, sol_s3_long.y[2], label='Lynx', color='red', lw=0.5)\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Chaotic dynamics (2000 months)')\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('Time [months]')\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('Population')\n",
    "axes[0].legend(loc='upper center')\n",
    "axes[0].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# State space (3D)\n",
    "ax3d = fig.add_subplot(122, projection='3d')\n",
    "axes[1].set_visible(False)\n",
    "ax3d.plot(sol_s3_long.y[0], sol_s3_long.y[1], sol_s3_long.y[2], lw=0.3, alpha=0.7)\n",
    "ax3d.set_xlabel('Plant Population')\n",
    "ax3d.set_ylabel('Hare Population')\n",
    "ax3d.set_zlabel('Lynx Population')\n",
    "ax3d.set_title('State space (2000 months)')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9bfbf00a-8ea4-409b-b615-423376999c3a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Deterministic Behavior"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e46a7845-5533-4676-a184-5f2614f0d9ae",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This code shows a simple Poincare plot. It takes the population at a specific population point (n) and plots this on the x-axis, then it takes the next point (n+1) and plots this on the y-axis. \n",
    "\n",
    "If the population dynamic was random it would show a cloud of scattered dots.\n",
    "However, our plots do not show random scattered points, instead they show a structured, smooth line, proving that the system is deterministic and not random. \n",
    "\n",
    "Even though the system fluctuates a lot and is unpredictable, they are following a mathematical rule where the state at n+1 is determined by the state at n. This proves that the system follows a path without randomness and it is therefore deterministic chaos.  "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 29,
   "id": "e3a6b0b5-5ef3-4882-9027-60d7bbfb9ca6",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1500x400 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "# Use a slice of the long simulation, skipping the initial transient\n",
    "P = sol_s3_long.y[0]\n",
    "H = sol_s3_long.y[1]\n",
    "L = sol_s3_long.y[2]\n",
    "\n",
    "# Skip the first ~500 points to remove transient behaviour\n",
    "start = 500\n",
    "end = 13000\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[0].scatter(P[start:end], P[start+1:end+1], s=1, alpha=0.5)\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Poincaré plot for Plants')\n",
    "axes[0].set_xlabel('plants $n$')\n",
    "axes[0].set_ylabel('plants $n+1$')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[1].scatter(H[start:end], H[start+1:end+1], s=1, alpha=0.5, color='orange')\n",
    "axes[1].set_title('Poincaré plot for Hares')\n",
    "axes[1].set_xlabel('hares $n$')\n",
    "axes[1].set_ylabel('hares $n+1$')\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[2].scatter(L[start:end], L[start+1:end+1], s=1, alpha=0.5, color='red')\n",
    "axes[2].set_title('Poincaré plot for Lynx')\n",
    "axes[2].set_xlabel('lynx $n$')\n",
    "axes[2].set_ylabel('lynx $n+1$')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f41b3c89-ad72-45d8-b34f-e8cb26df16e1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Sensitivity to Initial Conditions"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ea49feb7-3d78-44ac-88da-77fa778c78c8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "With the following plots we will want to prove that the system is **sensitive to initial conditions**. We do this by slightly changing the population of hares from 0.2 to 0.21, and solving for the two different cases.\n",
    "\n",
    "We then plot for the two cases and notice that this slight increase in hare populations causes incredibly different results for **all** populations and by the end of the (very very long) simulation they stabilize to different cycles and periods (to what seems to be a different kind of chaos). "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 33,
   "id": "426e8a44-4ab7-4954-9e1e-7cf241f0d2a8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1200x900 with 3 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "t_eval_long = np.linspace(0, 1000, 10000)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initial conditions\n",
    "y0 = [0.8, 0.2, 8]\n",
    "sol_orig = solve_ivp(plants_hare_lynx, (0, 1000), y0,\n",
    "                     args=(a1, a2, b1, b2, d1, d2),\n",
    "                     t_eval=t_eval_long, max_step=0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Slightly shifted initial conditions for the hares only (0.2 -> 0.21)\n",
    "y0_pert = [0.8, 0.21, 8]\n",
    "sol_pert = solve_ivp(plants_hare_lynx, (0, 1000), y0_pert,\n",
    "                     args=(a1, a2, b1, b2, d1, d2),\n",
    "                     t_eval=t_eval_long, max_step=0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(3, 1, figsize=(12, 9), sharex=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "species = ['Plants', 'Hares', 'Lynx']\n",
    "colours = ['green', 'orange', 'red']\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(3):\n",
    "    axes[i].plot(sol_orig.t, sol_orig.y[i], color=colours[i], lw=0.8,\n",
    "                label=f'{species[i]} (H₀ = 0.20)')\n",
    "    axes[i].plot(sol_pert.t, sol_pert.y[i], color=colours[i], lw=0.8,\n",
    "                linestyle='--', alpha=0.7,\n",
    "                label=f'{species[i]} (H₀ = 0.21)')\n",
    "    axes[i].set_ylabel(species[i])\n",
    "    axes[i].legend(loc='upper right')\n",
    "    axes[i].grid(True, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "axes[2].set_xlabel('Time [months]')\n",
    "axes[0].set_title('Sensitivity to initial conditions — trajectories diverge over time')\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()"
   ]
  },
 ],
